-- в”Ђв”Ђ Mailcow в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Mailcow is a free, open-source, Docker-based mail server and groupware suite that bundles Postfix, Dovecot, SOGo, Rspamd, and other components behind a modern web admin UI.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (optional paid support/hosting available)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(NULL, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Willich, Germany (The Infrastructure Company GmbH)$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$German$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Mailcow Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Mailcow review covering the Docker-based self-hosted mail server, groupware features, admin UI, pricing, pros and cons, and top alternatives in 2026.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Mailcow, commonly referred to by its project name mailcow: dockerized, is a free and open-source, self-hosted mail server and groupware suite distributed as a set of Docker containers. Rather than building its own mail transfer engine, mailcow composes well-established open-source components, Postfix for SMTP mail transfer, Dovecot for IMAP and POP3 access, Rspamd for spam and phishing filtering, ClamAV for antivirus scanning, SOGo for webmail and groupware (calendar, contacts, tasks), Redis for caching, MariaDB for the database layer, and Nginx as the web server, and wraps them in a unified, modern web-based administration panel. The project and its trademark are maintained by The Infrastructure Company GmbH, based in Willich, Germany, which also offers commercial hosting and support services around mailcow through its Servercow brand. Because it ships as Docker Compose services, mailcow can be deployed on any Linux host with Docker installed, making it more portable and modular than single-script alternatives, at the cost of requiring familiarity with Docker for setup and maintenance. Core features include full IMAP/IMAP+ and SMTP support with client autoconfiguration profiles, domain and mailbox aliasing, custom mail routing, multiple webmail options through SOGo, quota and per-domain admin delegation, enforced TLS with DANE and MTA-STS support, automatic Let's Encrypt certificates, outgoing DKIM signing, SPF and DMARC handling, anti-spoofing protections, greylisting, auto-learning spam filters, two-factor authentication, and a REST API for automation. Mailcow also supports ActiveSync-style mobile syncing and integrates a Snuffleupagus-hardened PHP layer and malicious-attachment blocking for additional security. The software itself is entirely free under an open-source license (GPLv3), and there is no paid software tier; the only costs are the server infrastructure it runs on and, optionally, commercial support contracts or managed mailcow hosting offered by third parties and by mailcow's maintaining company. Mailcow's target audience is system administrators, managed service providers, and privacy-focused organizations that want a full-featured, self-hosted alternative to hosted email and groupware suites like Google Workspace or Microsoft 365, without giving up webmail, calendaring, and contact sync. Its main competitors and alternatives in the self-hosted space include Mail-in-a-Box, Mailu, iRedMail, Modoboa, and Zimbra, with mailcow generally regarded as offering one of the more complete, modern-feeling admin experiences among Docker-based options, at the cost of somewhat higher resource requirements than lighter alternatives.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'f9d56d4e-fc0b-4b1a-9ea8-231bd20b02d4';

