-- в”Ђв”Ђ Mailgun в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Mailgun is a developer-focused transactional email API and SMTP relay service, now part of Sinch, used to send, validate, and track programmatic email at scale.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Usage-based subscription$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (100 emails/day); paid plans from $15/month$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2010, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Part of Sinch AB, Stockholm, Sweden (originally founded in San Francisco, California)$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Mailgun Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Mailgun review covering the transactional email API, deliverability tools, 2026 pricing tiers, pros and cons, and top alternatives for developers.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Mailgun is a transactional email API and SMTP relay service built for developers who need to send programmatic email, such as password resets, receipts, and notifications, from their applications. It was founded in 2010 by Ev Kontsevoy and Taylor Wakefield to address the lack of developer-friendly, API-first email infrastructure at the time, and the company went through Y Combinator in 2011. Mailgun was acquired by Rackspace in 2012, then spun back out as an independent company in 2017 under the name Pathwire (which also owned the Mailjet product). In September 2021, Sinch, a Swedish cloud communications platform (CPaaS) company, acquired Pathwire, and therefore Mailgun and Mailjet, for approximately 1.925 billion dollars, folding Mailgun into Sinch's broader messaging portfolio. Mailgun's architecture centers on a RESTful API and SMTP relay that developers integrate directly into their backend to send, receive, and track email programmatically, backed by infrastructure for handling large sending volumes, managing sender reputation, and processing bounces, complaints, and webhooks. Its core product lineup includes Send (the core sending API and SMTP relay), Optimize (a deliverability toolkit), Validate (real-time and bulk email address verification to reduce bounces), and Inspect (email rendering previews across clients, powered by Email on Acid). Additional features include inbound email routing and parsing, detailed logs and analytics, dedicated IP options, DKIM/SPF/DMARC configuration support, and webhooks for tracking opens, clicks, bounces, and spam complaints. Pricing is usage-based and tiered by monthly email volume: a free plan allows 100 emails per day; the Basic plan starts around 15 dollars per month for 10,000 emails; the Foundation plan is around 35 dollars per month for 50,000 emails and adds features like the template builder and more sending domains; the Scale plan is around 90 dollars per month for 100,000 emails and adds SAML SSO, dedicated IP pools, and send-time optimization; and an Enterprise tier offers custom volume pricing with dedicated deliverability services. Mailgun's target audience is software engineers and technical teams at SaaS companies, marketplaces, and platforms that need reliable transactional email infrastructure rather than marketing campaign tools. Its main competitors include SendGrid (Twilio), Amazon SES, Postmark, SparkPost, and Mailjet (its own sister product under Sinch). Mailgun differentiates itself with a developer-centric API design, strong email validation and deliverability tooling, and a long track record dating back to one of the earliest API-based email services, though pricing has become less generous over time as it has moved from an independent startup to a unit within a larger public communications company.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'e42b88f9-4910-4f3d-aacc-b784e0b8f957';

