-- в”Ђв”Ђ Mailman в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$GNU Mailman is a free, open-source mailing list management system used to run discussion and announcement mailing lists with web-based administration and archiving.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(1999, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$GNU Mailman Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$GNU Mailman review covering the open-source mailing list manager, Mailman 3 features, archiving, pricing, pros and cons, and alternatives in 2026.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$GNU Mailman is a free and open-source mailing list management system used to operate discussion lists, announcement lists, and digest-based email newsletters, distributed under the GNU General Public License as part of the GNU Project. Its origins trace back to the mid-1990s, when John Viega wrote an early version as a graduate student; after Viega lost his original source code in a hard drive crash around 1998, Ken Manheimer at the Corporation for National Research Initiatives picked up development while searching for a replacement for the older Majordomo mailing list tool. The first public release under the Mailman name arrived in 1999, and Barry Warsaw subsequently led the project for many years, with a broad group of contributors, before Abhilash Raj took over as lead maintainer more recently. There is no company behind Mailman; it is a community-maintained free software project written primarily in Python, with some C, and is one of the older continuously maintained pieces of internet mailing-list infrastructure still in active use, notably powering many open-source project mailing lists and academic/institutional lists. Architecturally, Mailman runs as a self-hosted mail list server that integrates with a Mail Transfer Agent like Postfix or Exim, processing incoming list mail, applying moderation and subscription rules, and redistributing messages to subscribers either individually or as digests. Mailman 3, released in April 2015, was the first major rewrite in over a decade, restructuring the system into separate components: Mailman Core for message processing, Postorius as the web-based administration and subscription interface, and HyperKitty as the web archive and searchable list-history browser, replacing the older Pipermail archiver from Mailman 2. Core features include list moderation and subscriber approval workflows, configurable posting permissions, automatic bounce processing, digest and MIME-stripped delivery options, DMARC mitigation strategies for lists carrying mail from strict sending domains, REST API access for automation, and a web archive with search. Because Mailman is entirely free open-source software, there is no vendor pricing; the only cost is the server infrastructure required to run it, and organizations can also find third-party managed Mailman hosting if they prefer not to self-host. Mailman's target audience includes open-source software projects, academic departments, nonprofits, professional associations, and any group that wants a traditional list-based email community rather than a modern newsletter tool. Its main alternatives include other open-source list managers like Sympa and Majordomo, along with modern hosted alternatives such as Google Groups or Discourse mailing-list mode for less traditional use cases. Mailman differentiates itself through its long history, deep moderation and administration controls purpose-built for real mailing-list governance, and its entrenched position as the default choice for many long-running open-source and institutional mailing lists.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '09b6e7a8-b810-4a31-9ecf-e4e0719bc76c';

